A DETAILED ARTICLE ON PUSHING A DIRECTORY TO GITHUB REPOSITORY
Note: We are using Git Bash for this
1. Locate the directory you want to push to GitHub and open it using git bash
How to Open a directory using Git Bash:
• I want to push the content of the directory “file_to_push” to GitHub
• Open the directory you wish to push to GitHub
• Left click in the background of the file and select Open Git Bash here


 
This the environment of Git Bash

2. List the content of the file using the command ls

3. Set up your GitHub email and username using the command
$ git config –global user.email “your email”
$ git config –global user.name “your username”
 


4. Use the command git init to create a new Git repository .git

5. Type the command git status to display the current status of the local repository

6. Type the command git add . to add all the files to be committed

7. Type the command git commit –m “How to push a file to GitHub”

8. Go to your GitHub account and create a repository with the same name with the directory you want to Push and copy Git URL
1
4
3
2



 
9. Add the remote repository by typing the command git remote add origin https://github.com/lemonntec/file_to_push.git

10. Type the command git branch -m main  

11. Then use the command git push -u origin main
 

12. Then, go to your GitHub account to see the files

